User Interface
**************

   XModule's GUI follows Commodore's 2.0 style guidelines.  Under
Kickstart 3.0 and above, XModule takes advantage of new OS capabilities
to enhance some aspects of the GUI.


 @{" Windows Layout " Link "Windows Layout"} 
 @{" Shortcut Keys " Link "Shortcut Keys"} 
 @{" On-Line Help " Link "On-Line Help"} 
 @{" Localization " Link "Localization"} 
 @{" Commodities " Link "Commodities"} 
 @{" Default Icons " Link "Default Icons"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Windows Layout" "XModule.guide/Windows Layout"
@Next "Shortcut Keys"
@Toc "User Interface"

Windows Layout
==============

   Gadget and menu layout is font sensitive, but using some fancy fonts
could result in a somewhat weird look.  If you are using a very big
font and a window becomes too big to fit in the screen, @{b}topaz/8@{ub} will be
used as a fallback for rendering that window.

   When you close a window, it will remember its position and size when
you open it again.  The same is true for window zooming operations.

   XModule will also try to make the active window visible by scrolling
the screen automatically.  This feature comes handy if you use a
virtual screen which is wider and/or taller than the default.


@EndNode

@Node "Shortcut Keys" "XModule.guide/Shortcut Keys"
@Next "On-Line Help"
@Prev "Windows Layout"
@Toc "User Interface"

Shortcut Keys
=============

   In all windows, the following shortcut keys are active:

ESC
     Close the active window.  Does not work with ToolBox window, as it
     would make it too easy to accidentally exit the program.

HELP
     Bring up AmigaGuide on-line help.  See @{"On-Line Help" Link "On-Line Help"}.

TAB
     Cycles forward through string and numeric gadgets within the active
     window.  @{b}SHIFT-TAB@{ub} will cycle backwards.  @{b}TAB@{ub} also activates the
     first string or numeric gadget if none is selected.

Alt-TAB
     Activates the next XModule window. @{b}ALT-SHIFT-TAB@{ub} activates the
     previous window.

RETURN
     Activate the first string or numeric gadget in the active window.

Cursor UP/DOWN
     Move up and down in a viewlist whenever the active window contains
     one.  @{b}SHIFT-Cursor@{ub} moves 5 items up/down. @{b}ALT-Cursor@{ub} moves to the
     top or to the bottom of the list.  This shortcut requires at least
     Kickstart 3.0.

   In addition, gadgets with underscored characters in labels, can be
operated hitting the highlighted key.  @{b}SHIFT-key@{ub} acts the opposite of
the unshifted key (sliders are decremented by one, cycle gadgets will
cycle backwards, etc).  Keyboard shortcuts will not work for all gadget
kinds under Kickstart 2.0.


@EndNode

@Node "On-Line Help" "XModule.guide/On-Line Help"
@Next "Localization"
@Prev "Shortcut Keys"
@Toc "User Interface"

On-Line Help
============

   This feature requires @{b}amigaguide.library@{ub}, which is distributed with
Workbench version 2.1 and up, and @{b}XModule.guide@{ub} located in the current
directory or in the same directory of XModule's executable or in the
@{b}HELP:language/@{ub} directory, where @{b}language@{ub} is any of your Locale
preferred languages.  AmigaGuide(TM) is also available as a freely
distributable package for 1.3-2.0 users.

   To get help on a gadget, press HELP while the mouse pointer is over
the gadget.  To get help on a string gadget, activate it and press
HELP.  Hitting HELP while the mouse isn't over a gadget, will give you
help on the active window.

   To get help on a menu item, hilight the item and press HELP while
keeping the right mouse button pressed.


@EndNode

@Node "Localization" "XModule.guide/Localization"
@Next "Commodities"
@Prev "On-Line Help"
@Toc "User Interface"

Localization
============

   Localization requires @{b}locale.library@{ub},  which is distributed with
Workbench version 2.1 and up, and the catalog file @{b}XModule.catalog@{ub}
located in the same directory of XModule's executable or in the
@{b}LOCALE:catalogs/language/@{ub} directory, where @{b}langage@{ub} is is any of your
Locale preferred languages.

   If you speak a language for which a catalog isn't yet available,
please consider writing it yourself and then send it to me, so it will
be included in the next release of XModule.  Look at the empty catalog
translation file @{b}Empty.ct@{ub} in the @{b}Catalogs/@{ub}.  It can be used to create
new catalog descriptions for XModule.  Then, use a tool like `FlexCat',
`KitKat' or `CatComp' to compile it into a catalog file.


@EndNode

@Node "Commodities" "XModule.guide/Commodities"
@Next "Default Icons"
@Prev "Localization"
@Toc "User Interface"

Commodities support
===================

   XModule is a Commodity and can be controlled by the Commodities
Exchange program.

   XModule will pop up when its hotkey is typed; the main window will
activate and the screen will move to the front.  If XModule's interface
is hidden, it will be revealed.

   The user interface can be hidden with the Exchange program.  When
the user interface is hidden, the only ways you have to still operate
XModule is through the ARexx port or the AppIcon.

   You can also control XModule by sending the following signals to its
process:

@{b}*@{ub}@{b}CTRL-C@{ub}
     Quit XModule.

@{b}*@{ub}@{b}CTRL-D@{ub}
     Disable the Commodities broker (equivalent to selecting @{b}Inactive@{ub}
     with Commodities Exchange).

@{b}*@{ub}@{b}CTRL-E@{ub}
     Enable the Commodities broker (equivalent to selecting @{b}Active@{ub} with
     Commodities Exchange).

@{b}*@{ub}@{b}CTRL-F@{ub}
     Deiconify XModule (equivalent to double-clicking on the AppIcon).


@EndNode

@Node "Default Icons" "XModule.guide/Default Icons"
@Prev "Commodities"
@Toc "User Interface"

Default Icons
=============

   When XModule creates an icon for a file, it looks for the user
preferred icon for the type of data being saved.

   The template icons can be placed in the @{b}Icons@{ub} drawer which is
located in the same drawer where the XModule executable resides.
p{No Value For "rgname"} will also look for its icons in the @{b}ENV:Sys/@{ub}
directory.  If you choose to use @{b}ENV:Sys/@{ub}, you will probably want to
store the icons in @{b}ENVARC:Sys/@{ub} to have them copied automatically to
@{b}ENV:Sys/@{ub} every time the system boots up.

   Template icons should be only of type @{i}Project@{ui}.  When XModule does
not find a template icon, it uses the default Project icon instead.

   Whenever the default icon does not have its own default tool, it
will be set to XModule's executable.

   The following default icons are supported:

-@{b}def_Module@{ub}
-@{b}def_Instrument@{ub}

@EndNode

